# Domain Layer

The innermost layer. Pure business model and rules. **Zero framework dependencies**
(no Spring, JPA, Jackson, Lombok annotations tied to infra). Plain Java only.

## Structure

```
domain/
├── model/        # Entities + Value Objects
├── repository/   # Repository PORTS (interfaces only)
├── service/      # Domain service PORTS / pure domain logic
└── event/        # Domain events
```

## Entities & Value Objects (`model/`)

- Encapsulate invariants in the constructor — an object is **always valid** once created.
- Prefer immutability: `final` fields, no setters. Use methods to produce new states.
- Value Objects (e.g. `Email`) wrap primitives and self-validate. Avoid primitive obsession.

```java
// ✅ GOOD: self-validating value object, no framework
public final class Email {
    private final String value;
    public Email(String value) {
        if (value == null || !value.contains("@"))
            throw new InvalidEmailException(value);
        this.value = value.toLowerCase();
    }
    public String value() { return value; }
}
```

## Repository ports (`repository/`)

- **Interfaces only**, expressed in domain terms. Implemented in `infrastructure/persistence`.
- Methods speak the ubiquitous language and return domain models, never JPA entities.

```java
public interface UserRepository {
    Optional<User> findById(UserId id);
    Optional<User> findByEmail(Email email);
    User save(User user);
}
```

## Domain services (`service/`)

- Interfaces for capabilities the domain needs but cannot implement itself
  (e.g. `PasswordHasher`, `TokenGenerator`). Implemented in `infrastructure`.

## Domain events (`event/`)

- Immutable records describing something that happened: `UserRegisteredEvent`.
- Past tense names. Carry only the data needed by handlers.

## Rules

- Throw **domain-specific exceptions** (e.g. `InvalidEmailException`), not generic ones.
- No `@Entity`, `@Component`, `@Autowired`, or any annotation here.
- No I/O (DB, HTTP, files) — that belongs to infrastructure.
